```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <cctype> // for tolower()

using namespace std;

int countWordOccurrences(const string& filename, and const string& word) {
    ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file) {
        cerr << "Error opening file: " << filename << endl;
        return -1;
    }

    int count = 0;
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        istringstream iss(line);
        string token;
        while (iss >> token) {
            // Convert to lowercase for case-insensitive matching
            for (char& c : token) {
                c = tolower(c);
            }
            if (token == word) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }
    file.close();
    return count;
}

int main() {
    string filename = "example.txt"; // replace with your file name
    string word = "hello"; // replace with your word

    int occurrences = countWordOccurrences(filename, word);
    if (occurrences != -1) {
        cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" occurs " << occurrences << " times in the file." << endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```
Here's how the program works:

1. The `countWordOccurrences` function takes two arguments: `filename` and `word`. It opens the file specified by `filename` and reads it line by line.
2. For each line, it uses an `istringstream` to tokenize the line into individual words.
3. It converts each token to lowercase using the `tolower` function from `<cctype>` to perform case-insensitive matching.
4. It checks if the token matches the specified `word`, and if so, increments a counter.
5. The function returns the total count of occurrences of the word in the file.
6. In `main`, we call the `countWordOccurrences` function with the specified file name and word, and print the result to the console.

Note that this program assumes that the word is a single token (i.e., not a phrase) and that the file contains only ASCII characters. If you need to handle more complex cases, you may need to modify the program accordingly.

